{"title_page": "Jeff Borowiak", "text_new": "{{short description|American tennis player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name                              = Jeff Borowiak\n|image                             = \n|caption                           = \n|fullname                          = \n|country                           = {{USA}}\n|residence                         = [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|WA]] United States\n|birth_date                        = {{birth date and age|1949|09|25}}\n|birth_place                       = [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]], [[California|CA]], USA\n|height                            = {{convert|1.93|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|college                           = \n|turnedpro                         = 1968<small> (amateur tour from 1967)\n|retired                           = 1986\n|plays                             = Right-handed (1-handed backhand)\n|careerprizemoney                  = \n|singlesrecord                     = 276-291<small> (at [[ATP Tour]] level, [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] level, and in [[Davis Cup]])\n|singlestitles                     = 5\n|highestsinglesranking             = No. 20 (August 30, 1977)\n|AustralianOpenresult              = 4R ([[1982 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1982]])\n|FrenchOpenresult                  = 3R ([[1978 French Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1978]])\n|Wimbledonresult                   = 4R ([[1971 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1971]], [[1981 Australian Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1981]])\n|USOpenresult                      = 3R ([[1968 US Open \u2013 Men's Singles|1968]])\n|doublesrecord                     = 146-211<small> (at ATP Tour level, Grand Slam level, and in Davis Cup)\n|doublestitles                     = 3\n|highestdoublesranking             =\n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult      =\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult          = 3R (1977, 1978)\n| WimbledonDoublesresult           = 3R (1974, 1976, 1977)\n| USOpenDoublesresult              = QF (1971)\n}}\n\n'''Jeff Borowiak''' (born September 25, 1949) is a former professional [[tennis player]] from the United States, who won five singles and three doubles titles during his professional career, reaching a career-high [[Association of Tennis Professionals|ATP]] singles ranking of World No. 20 in August 1977.\n\n==Personal==\nBorowiak is also an accomplished musician, mastering the flute and the piano. He was also indirectly involved in the formation of the group [[Metallica]] when he invested in his friend and Danish fellow player [[Torben Ulrich]]'s son band Lars Rocket, which later became Metallica.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n==Tennis career==\nBorowiak played number one singles on one of the greatest collegiate tennis team of all time for the [[UCLA Bruins#Tennis|UCLA Bruins]].  [[Haroon Rahim]] played number two singles, [[Jimmy Connors]] played at number three.  Borowiak and Connors were NCAA champions, while Rahim remains the youngest player ever to represent his country in the [[Davis Cup]] competition.\n\nBorowiak was ATP Comeback Player of the Year in 1981.<ref>[http://www.atpworldtour.com/Tennis/Players/Bo/J/Jeff-Borowiak.aspx ATP Player Profile]</ref>\n\nBorowiak was inducted into the [[Intercollegiate Tennis Association#Hall of Fame|Intercollegiate Tennis Association (ITA) Hall of Fame]].<ref>[http://www.itatennis.com/AboutITA/HOF/Mens.htm ITA Men's Hall of Fame]</ref>\n\n==Career finals==\n\n===Singles: 11 (5 titles \u2013 6 runners-up)===\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:20px\" class=\"unsortable\"|No.\n!style=\"width:60px\"|Date\n!style=\"width:180px\"|Tournament\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Opponent\n!style=\"width:150px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| 1.\n| Oct 1971\n| Cologne WCT, Germany\n| Carpet\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Bob Lutz (tennis)|Robert Lutz]]\n| 3\u20136, 7\u20136, 3\u20136, 1\u20136\n|-\n| style=\